From STL components above:

  • An increasing linear trend. The trend line shows linear incrasing. The passenger numbers increase over this period.
  • It seems like seasonal
  • The residuals variance seems to increase a little bit through time, showing that the series exhibits a little more random behavior at the end.
  • A multiplicative process. Because the magnitude of the seasonal component changes with time, so the series is multiplicative. Otherwise, the series is additive. In other words, because when the number of passengers increases, the seasonality increases as well. So the it is a multiplicateive process

3.3.1 Task 2: Autoregressive modeling¶

  • Apply the exponential smoothing model and ARIMA model
  • Some preprocessing based on the STL result may need for running the autoregressive modeling.
  • Explain what underlying data generating processes the results may reveal.

  • A stationary time series is one whose statistical properties do not depend on the time at which the series is observed. No trend, no season, can be cyclic

  • Exponential smoothings models are appropriate for non-stationary data, to forecast stationary-time series

  1. simple exponential smoothing: suitable for Few data points, Irregular data, No seasonality or trend.
  2. Holts winter exponential smoothing: suitable Data has a trend. Use the multiplicative version, unless the data has been logged before.
  • ARIMA models should be used on stationary data only, to forecast stationary time series
  1. A weighted sum of lagged values of the series (Auto-regressive (AR) part)
  2. A weighted sum of lagged forecasted errors of the series (Moving-average (MA) part)
  3. A difference of the time series (Integrated (I) part)
In [381]:
# define a function to test if data is stationary or not.
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

def stationarity(timeseries):

    # check stationarity based on statistics.
    rolmean=timeseries.rolling(window=12).mean()
    rolstd=timeseries.rolling(window=12).std()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,3))
    ax_std = ax.twinx()
    actual=ax.plot(timeseries, color='b', label='Original data', alpha =0.7)
    mean_6=ax.plot(rolmean, color='b', label='Rolling Mean',linestyle='dashed',alpha =0.7) 
    std_6=ax_std.plot(rolstd, color='r', label='Rolling Std',alpha =0.7)
    #std_6=ax_std.plot(rolstd, 'y.', label='Rolling Std')
    ax.set_ylabel('#Airpassengers', color = 'b')
    ax_std.set_ylabel('stadard deviation', color = 'r')
    ax.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    ax_std.legend(loc = 'lower right')
    ax.set_title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    
    # Using ADF (Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test) to check stationarity
    print('Dickey-Fuller Test: ')
    dftest=adfuller(timeseries.values, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput=pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','Lags Used','No. of Obs'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput)

3.3.2 Task 1: Educational Guess¶

  • For the 2020 time series, make an educational guess on how many change points are in the data. As a reference for making an educated guess, a timeline of the virus-containment measures can be found on Wikipedia3.

Virus-containment measures timeline:

  • 28 February 2020, banned all events with more than 1,000 participants
  • 16 March 2020, a State of Extraordinary Situation
  • 20 March 2020, all gatherings of more than five people in public spaces were banned
  • Beginning in late April until June 2020, the measures were gradually removed in several phases
  • October 2020, new measures were imposed as cases surged again

Educational guess: there could be 3 change points

  • The first change point could be near March 2020, as the first several measures were issued between the end of February to middle March 2020.
  • The second change point could be near May 2020, as measures were gradually removed from late April to June 2020
  • The third change point could be in October, because of the measures in October, 2020.

# change point detection by comparing changes in mean
# need to specify the number of change points

def change_window(ts,df,n):

  algo = rpt.Window(width=30, model="l2").fit(ts)
  bkps = algo.predict(n_bkps = n)
  
  bkps_date = df.loc[bkps[:-1], :]['DATE'].to_list() 
  print(f'The change points are on days: {bkps}')
  print(f'The change points are on date: {bkps_date}' )
  fig, (ax,) = rpt.display(ped.values, bkps, bkps, figsize=(12, 3))
  plt.show()

# define a function to calculate 7 acf features (with the same result from R feat_acf)

from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf 

def feat_acf(data, season = None, col_name=None):
  
  data = data # original data
  diff1_data = data[1:] - data[:-1] # differenced data
  diff2_data = diff1_data[1:] - diff1_data[:-1] # twice differenced data
  
  # calculate acf coefficients
  acf_all = acf(data, nlags =30)
  acf_all = acf_all[1:] 
  diff1_acf = acf(diff1_data, nlags =30)
  diff1_acf = diff1_acf[1:]
  diff2_acf = acf(diff2_data, nlags =30)
  diff2_acf = diff2_acf[1:]

  # the first autocorrelation coefficient from the original data
  acf1 = acf_all[0]  
  # the sum of squares of the first ten autocorrelation coefficients from the original data
  acf10  = sum(acf_all[0:10]*acf_all[0:10])
  # the first autocorrelation coefficient from the differenced data
  diff1_acf1 = diff1_acf[0]
  # the sum of squares of the first ten autocorrelation coefficients from the differenced data
  diff1_acf10 = sum(diff1_acf[0:10]*diff1_acf[0:10])
  # the first autocorrelation coefficient from the twice differenced data
  diff2_acf1 = diff2_acf[0]
  # the sum of squares of the first ten autocorrelation coefficients from the twice differenced data
  diff2_acf10 = sum(diff2_acf[0:10]*diff2_acf[0:10])

  # For seasonal data, the autocorrelation coefficient at the first seasonal lag
  if season == None:
    season_acf1 = 'NA'
  else:
    season_acf1 = acf_all[season-1]

  # define a dataframe as output
  features = ['acf1', 'acf10', 'diff1_acf1', 'diff1_acf10', 'diff2_acf1', 'diff2_acf10','season_acf1']
  df_acf_feature = pd.DataFrame(features, columns=['acf_features'])
  df_acf_feature[col_name] = [acf1, acf10, diff1_acf1, diff1_acf10, diff2_acf1, diff2_acf10, season_acf1]

  return df_acf_feature

From the table of acf_features above:

  • segment 1 has smaller acf1 and acf10 than segment 2
  • segment 1 has larger diff1_acf1 and diff1_acf10 than segment 2
  • segment 1 has larger diff2_acf1 and diff2_acf10 than segment 2
  • segment 1 is seasonal data. segment 2 is not seasonal data

acf features:

  • The first acf is the correlation between values that are one time period apart (1 day for this case)
  • The sum of the first ten squared autocorrelation coefficients is a useful summary of how much autocorrelation there is in a series, regardless of lag.
  • The diff1_acf computes autocorrelations of the changes in the series between periods.
  • Second differencing helps make stationary if first differencing does not work.

Conclusion:

  • For the original data: correlation between values that are one day apart is smaller for segment1. There is less autocorrelation in segment 1 than in segment 2
  • For the differenced data (daily changes): there is larger autocorrelation in segment 1 than in segment 2 for the daily changes.
  • For the second differenced data: segment 1 is more stationary than segment 2
  • Segment 1 is seasonal data with a season of 7 days. Segment 2 is not.
